When You Clone a Repo
--------------------
git clone https://github.com/myorg/ecommerce.git

# Git automatically creates a nickname called "origin"
# origin = https://github.com/myorg/ecommerce.git

-------------------
Proof — Check What Origin Points To
-------------

git remote -v

# Output:
# origin  https://github.com/myorg/ecommerce.git (fetch)
# origin  https://github.com/myorg/ecommerce.git (push)
----------------------------------------
# Without nickname — type full URL every time 😫
git fetch https://github.com/myorg/ecommerce.git

# With origin nickname — short and clean ✅
git fetch origin
--------------------------------------
git merge main         # merge your local main into current branch
git merge origin/main  # merge remote's main into current branch ✅
---------------------------------------------------------------------
git merge  origin/main
    │         │    │
    │         │    └── branch name (main)
    │         └── remote nickname (origin = GitHub)
    └── merge command
--------------------------------------------------
main           → your local branch
origin/main    → your local copy of the remote branch (updated when you fetch)
